th Indian Society Towards the Close of the Eighteenth Century -- t14. Celebration of Religious Diversity in Agra: Reading the Observations of Nazir Akbarabadi -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores state formation, social fabrics and cultural mores of medieval India from 1200-1800.The states of medieval India operated under a ruling class that was largely Muslim, colouring our understanding of the history of the period. Increased availability of Persian chronicles, emergence of a class of professional historians and progressive forces emanating from the anti-colonial movement have led to new approaches to the period.Situating Medieval India covers more than 6 centuries, from the Delhi Sultanate to the arrival of Europeans. Topics covered include approaches to exercise of sovereign power in medieval states and the social identity of government officers, Dulla Bhatti's revolt against the Mughal State, modes of resistance in the state of Punjab, and religious diversity in Agra. The author also examines scientific and technical innovations, and the artworks of Mushtaqi, Jahangir and Bhandari. The book opens up medieval India in all its complexity and richness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAsian Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aAkbar.  aAlauddin Khalji.  aAmir Khusrau.  aFatawa-i Jahandari.  aFiroz Shah Tughluq.  aGhiasuddin Balban.  aGuru Nanak.  aJalaluddin Khalji.  aMongols.  aMughal.  aMuhammad bin Tughluq.  aQarlugh.  aShah Husain.  aShams Siraj Afif.  aSultan Mahmud.  aTarikh-i Firoz Shahi.  aZamindars.  aZiauddin Barani.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311142849940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978180